stories.description:
CONTEXT: After S75, section summaries exist for documents. This story changes pregenerate() in SummarizationService so that when section summaries are available, it uses them as the map-reduce input instead of raw chunks. This reduces the Iliad's document summary generation from 100+ sequential LLM calls to a single LLM call over the concatenated section summaries. This directly fixes the 15-minute timeout problem. FAST PATH LOGIC — In app/services/summarizer.py, add a private async method _build_section_summary_input(self, document_id: str) -> str | None. Implementation: (1) Query SectionSummaryModel for all rows matching document_id, ordered by unit_index. (2) If fewer than 3 rows found, return None (not enough coverage to trust). (3) Build a markdown string: join all rows as '## {heading}
{content}

'. Return this string. MODIFY pregenerate() — The existing pregenerate() fetches chunks and runs map-reduce. Change it to: (1) First call _build_section_summary_input(document_id). (2) If it returns a non-None string (the fast path): use that string directly as the input_text for all three modes (one_sentence, executive, detailed). No map-reduce needed. Each mode is one LLM call on the section summary input. Store the section summary input as mode='_section_reduce' in SummaryModel (following Core Belief #18: cache expensive intermediates — same pattern as existing '_map_reduce' mode). (3) If it returns None (the slow path — no section summaries, pre-v2 document or section summarization was offline): fall through to the existing chunk-based map-reduce. This preserves backward compatibility for all existing documents. IMPORTANT: The '_section_reduce' row should be stored once and reused across all modes, exactly like '_map_reduce'. If '_section_reduce' already exists for this document, skip recomputing it. PERFORMANCE REQUIREMENT: For the Iliad with 100 section summary units: _build_section_summary_input() is a DB query (< 100ms). Each of the three summary modes (one_sentence, executive, detailed) is a single LLM call on the concatenated section summaries (~30-60 sec each). Total pregenerate time: < 3 minutes for Iliad. Compare to v1 which timed out at 15+ minutes. CACHE INVALIDATION: When section summaries for a document are regenerated (e.g. force_refresh ingest), the '_section_reduce' summary row must be deleted so pregenerate() recomputes it. Add a method async def invalidate_section_reduce_cache(self, document_id: str) -> None that deletes SummaryModel rows where document_id matches and mode='_section_reduce'. Call this at the start of generate() in SectionSummarizerService when regenerating. TESTS — tests/test_document_summary_fast_path.py: (a) test_fast_path_used_when_section_summaries_exist: insert 10 SectionSummaryModel rows for a doc, call pregenerate() with mock LiteLLM, assert mock was called exactly once per mode (not dozens of times as in map-reduce). (b) test_slow_path_fallback_when_no_section_summaries: no SectionSummaryModel rows, call pregenerate(), assert existing map-reduce logic runs (verify by checking that LiteLLM was called with chunk batches). (c) test_section_reduce_cached_as_db_row: after fast path runs, assert SummaryModel has a row with mode='_section_reduce'. (d) test_fast_path_skipped_with_fewer_than_3_units: insert 2 rows, assert slow path is taken. SMOKE — scripts/smoke/S76.sh: (1) Ingest a document that already has section summaries (from S75 smoke). (2) POST /summarize/{id} with mode=executive and force_refresh=true. (3) Assert HTTP 200 and streaming response contains non-empty content. (4) GET /summarize/{id}/cached, assert 'executive' key present in response. (5) Exit 0.

CONTEXT: S77 created the LangGraph skeleton with stub nodes. This story implements the real logic for each strategy node. Each node is a self-contained async function that reads from ChatState and writes back to it. SUMMARY_NODE — Replace the stub. Logic: (1) Fetch the 'executive' summary from SummaryModel for the requested document(s). For scope='single' and one document: query SummaryModel where document_id=state.doc_ids[0] and mode='executive', return content. For scope='all': fetch the most recent LibrarySummaryModel where mode='executive'. (2) If no summary found: fall through to search_node by setting state.intent='factual' and returning state (the graph will re-route on the next step — add a conditional edge: if summary_node finds nothing, re-route to search_node). (3) If found: set state.chunks=[] (no retrieval needed), state.section_context=summary_content, state.answer='' (synthesize_node will generate the final answer using section_context as primary input). GRAPH_NODE — Replace the stub. Logic: (1) Extract entity names from the question using a simple regex approach: find capitalized words and quoted strings. (2) Query Kuzu: for each extracted entity, MATCH (e:Entity {name: $name})-[r]-(related) RETURN e.name, type(r), related.name LIMIT 20. (3) Format graph results as a structured string: 'Knowledge graph connections:
{entity} --{relation}--> {related}
...'. (4) If Kuzu is unavailable or returns 0 results: set state.section_context=None and fall through (return state with intent overridden to 'factual', triggering re-route to search_node). (5) Also run hybrid retrieval (k=5) as a grounding supplement — set state.chunks to these 5 chunks. State.section_context = graph_result_string. Wrap all Kuzu calls in try/except — graph failure must never fail the answer. COMPARATIVE_NODE — Replace the stub. Logic: (1) Run hybrid retrieval twice: once for each side of the comparison (detect sides by splitting on 'compare', 'versus', 'vs.', 'difference between', 'vs'). If two sides cannot be detected, run a single retrieval. (2) Interleave results: [side_a_chunk_1, side_b_chunk_1, side_a_chunk_2, side_b_chunk_2, ...]. (3) Write interleaved chunks to state.chunks. Set state.section_context to a header: 'Comparison query: {question}'. The synthesize_node will format the answer structurally. SEARCH_NODE — Replace the stub with full implementation. Logic: (1) Use rewritten_question if available, else question. (2) Call existing hybrid retrieval (HybridRetriever, k=10). (3) For each retrieved chunk that has a section_id: look up its SectionSummaryModel row by section_id (batch DB lookup, not per-chunk). (4) For each chunk, prepend section summary if found: format as '### {section_heading}
{section_summary}
---
{chunk_text}'. This gives the LLM section-level context without retrieving entire sections. (5) Write augmented chunks to state.chunks. SYNTHESIZE_NODE — Replace the stub. This node is the LLM call. Logic: (1) Build context string from state.chunks (augmented) and state.section_context (graph results, section summary, or library summary). (2) Build system prompt based on intent: 'summary' -> 'Answer using the provided document summary. Be concise and structured.'; 'relational' -> 'Answer using the knowledge graph connections and the supporting passages. Name the entities clearly.'; 'comparative' -> 'Compare the two subjects using the provided passages. Structure as: Subject A: ... Subject B: ...'; default -> existing QA system prompt. (3) Call LiteLLM with streaming=True. (4) Accumulate tokens and write to state.stream_tokens. (5) Parse final accumulated text using existing _split_response() to extract answer, citations, confidence, not_found. (6) Write these fields to state. The SSE streaming in stream_answer() reads from state.stream_tokens as the graph runs (use LangGraph's streaming API or astream_events). IMPORTANT: Do not duplicate any existing logic. Import _split_response, _enrich_citation_titles, _maybe_rewrite_query from existing qa.py locations. Refactor them into app/services/ if they are currently defined inside stream_answer() (move to module level). TESTS — tests/test_chat_graph_nodes.py: (a) test_summary_node_returns_executive_summary: insert a SummaryModel row with mode='executive', run summary_node, assert state.section_context == that content. (b) test_summary_node_falls_through_when_no_summary: no summary in DB, assert intent overridden to 'factual'. (c) test_graph_node_falls_through_on_kuzu_error: mock Kuzu to raise exception, assert no exception raised and intent overridden to 'factual'. (d) test_search_node_augments_chunks_with_section_summaries: insert SectionSummaryModel rows, run search_node with mock retrieval returning chunks with matching section_ids, assert output chunk texts contain '---' separator and section heading. (e) test_comparative_node_interleaves_results: mock retrieval to return 3 chunks per side, assert state.chunks alternates sides. (f) test_synthesize_node_calls_litellm: mock LiteLLM, run synthesize_node, assert LiteLLM called with system prompt containing intent-appropriate text. SMOKE — scripts/smoke/S78.sh: (1) POST /qa with question='Who is Achilles?', assert HTTP 200 and answer non-empty. (2) POST /qa with question='Summarize this document', assert HTTP 200. (3) Both responses must return within 30 seconds. Exit 0.

